onal weight gain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Preterm birth","Fetal macrosomia","Gestational diabetes mellitus","Childhood obesity","Prolonged labour"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOf the options, \u003Cstrong\u003Epreterm birth \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most significant risk associated with inadequate gestational weight gain. Insufficient weight gain during pregnancy is linked to increased risk of delivering before 37 weeks gestation and having a low birth weight infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent incorrect associations:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFetal macrosomia\u003C/strong\u003E is actually associated with excessive rather than inadequate gestational weight gain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGestational diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E risk is more closely related to pre-pregnancy BMI than gestational weight gain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChildhood obesity\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with excessive gestational weight gain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged labour\u003C/strong\u003E has no clear association with inadequate gestational weight gain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Institute of Medicine guidelines recommend specific weight gain ranges based on pre-pregnancy BMI to help prevent these adverse outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insufficient gestational weight gain increases the risk of preterm birth and low birth weight infants.","The Institute of Medicine recommends specific weight gain ranges during pregnancy based on pre-pregnancy BMI to optimize maternal and fetal outcomes."],"references":["Giouleka S, Tsakiridis I, Kostakis N, Koutsouki G, Kalogiannidis I, Mamopoulos A, Athanasiadis A, 